The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Car sales jump 18% in August

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Sept. 11: Car sales shrugged off interest rate jitters and posted an 18 per cent jump in sales in August. The rally was led by Maruti Udyog on the back of heavy discounts offered by the company. However, it was a downhill ride for motorcycles, which recorded an 11.09 per cent drop in sales. 

 According to figures released by the Society of Automobile Manufacturers (SIAM), vehicle sales dropped 1.67 per cent to 7,39,157 units from 7,51,775 units in the corresponding month a year ago. Passenger car sales were at 98,893 units compared with 83,864 units a year ago.

 Maruti Udyog posted a 24 per cent increase in sales at 52,055 units against 41,728 units in the same period last year. The car makers Smile India Smile scheme offered discounts of up to Rs 40,000. Hyundai Motor India Ltd sold 16,115 units compared with 16,067 units in the corresponding period a year ago. Tata Motors, however, recorded a 3.56 per cent decline in sales at 13,588 units.

 Car companies feel that the second half of the year will be better. The festival season is round the corner and companies are betting good. Also, with interest rates coming down and good monsoons in some parts of the country, sales should get better and release the pressure on companies, said Jnaneswar Sen, senior manager (marketing) of Honda Siel Cars India.

 General Motors India clocked a healthy growth of 18.63 per cent at 3,017 units against 2,543 units in the same month last year. The company reported good sales in its compact car segment. 




